WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.240
me in the past, I have the very fun job of running growth for RStudio Cloud. In terms of housekeeping

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:10.480
for today's event, we're going to have a guest presenter run through a presentation for the

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:14.400
first half of today's session, and then we're going to jump into a Q&A for the second half.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:20.799
Now, I have a colleague on the back end who's going to be hopefully juggling some questions

00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:26.000
as they trickle in via chat, and if you need to leave early, please don't worry, we will be

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:31.040
recording this. And please keep in mind that the focus of these events are to address the

00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:35.520
questions most important to all of you. Now, with that being said, I'm super excited to

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:40.880
introduce today's guest, Dr. Brian Anderson, Associate Dean and Professor at University

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:46.000
of Missouri-Kansas City. Pete, thanks so much, appreciate it.

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:54.480
Thank you, everybody, and welcome. I'm so pleased that you all take the time to join us. And Pete,

00:00:54.480 --> 00:01:00.560
thank you and the team at RStudio and RStudio Cloud for giving me the opportunity to chat about

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:07.599
a topic that I'm very passionate about, but also one that as an institution, we are very much

00:01:07.599 --> 00:01:14.000
still working through and still trying to figure out how we're going to be able to

00:01:14.239 --> 00:01:20.239
working through and still addressing, you know, our own path forward. I think it kind of reflects

00:01:20.239 --> 00:01:27.279
the very rapid pace and development, you know, in this field. And so I'm looking forward to

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:35.519
sharing some thoughts about the challenges that we have identified as we look to move towards a

00:01:35.519 --> 00:01:39.839
kind of a cloud-centric solution for our undergraduate and graduate programs,

00:01:40.639 --> 00:01:45.680
and also talk about some of the opportunities ahead. And then, you know, certainly the chance

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:50.400
to hear from you all, answer some questions, and have some dialogue. So

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:59.680
why don't we go ahead and get started with the presentation. So in my role as Executive Associate

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:06.000
Dean at the Block School, I oversee all of our degree programs. And so this notion of how do we

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:13.440
leverage new and emerging technologies to teach topics, you know, certainly analytics at scale,

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:21.759
is very much in my area of responsibility. So let me give a little bit of context about

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:27.839
the Block School and the University of Missouri-Kansas City. So the University of Missouri-Kansas

00:02:27.839 --> 00:02:32.639
City is part of the University of Missouri system. There are four campuses in our system. You may be

00:02:32.639 --> 00:02:43.839
familiar with our larger sister campus in Columbia, Mizzou. We serve the Kansas City area

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:49.440
in the Kansas City region. So by Carnegie classification, we are a research-to school. So we

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:57.279
are a research-centric school, but we also are very much a public urban research university school.

00:02:57.919 --> 00:03:07.119
So as part of that mission, our student population very much reflects the diversity of the Kansas

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:13.679
City region. So for example, we have a very large percentage of our students that are first

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:18.399
generation college students. We have a large percentage of our students that come from

00:03:18.399 --> 00:03:25.119
historically underrepresented communities. Our student population reflects, you know,

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:30.639
significant heterogeneity in socioeconomic background. And so when we think about

00:03:31.199 --> 00:03:37.600
leveraging technologies, it's important to kind of keep that student body population in mind.

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:43.679
Drilling down a little bit more, the Block School is what we would consider to be kind of a medium

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:50.399
sized business school. So we have about 2000 total students. Our single largest degree program

00:03:50.399 --> 00:03:56.559
is our professional MBA, which has about 600 students in that program.

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:03.919
We focus on business analytics. I think that context is important here.

00:04:05.199 --> 00:04:11.119
Most of what you would think of as kind of core knowledge, core technologies would be very similar

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:21.440
in kind of a standard computer science intro course or a kind of a basic undergraduate

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:26.880
statistics course or a core graduate statistics course. But it's really taught from an analytics

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:32.959
frame or excuse me, a business frame. So it's grounded in a business conversation

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:39.200
and addressing business problems. And I think that's important to keep in mind that everything

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:45.679
really kind of needs to tie to our core business context. I think an analogy might be say a health

00:04:45.679 --> 00:04:51.519
analytics space where the statistics, the analytics coursework behind it would reflect

00:04:51.519 --> 00:04:59.359
very common elements, but it would be taught in a health frame. So we offer analytics specializations,

00:04:59.359 --> 00:05:05.760
what would effectively be like a major. We also have a smaller interest area and then we have a

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:11.920
graduate certificate. And then the last contextual piece that I think is very important is the

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:18.000
employment base within Kansas City. So most of our students come from the Kansas City region and they

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:23.440
will work in the Kansas City region. And Kansas City is very fortunate that we have a very strong

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:30.000
and diversified economic base. Our largest single sector is healthcare, but that's still only about

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:37.600
a fifth of the economy here in Kansas City. And I think that's important for us because as we think

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:45.200
about preparing students with analytic skill sets, it's important that they are likely to serve in a

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:51.200
variety of different verticals. It would be a disservice to our students, for example, if we

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:57.600
focused on one particular context. And so it's important that the skill sets that we provide

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:04.880
and the training that we provide really reflect the heterogeneity of employment that our students

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:09.359
are likely to have here in the Kansas City region. So that's just a little bit of context, but let's

00:06:09.359 --> 00:06:16.079
let's jump in and talk about the problems that we're trying to solve. Because this really frames

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:26.399
why we are looking towards the cloud for teaching analytics at scale. And I would put all of these

00:06:26.959 --> 00:06:35.200
questions with a pretty similar ranking. And so as we think about leveraging technology

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:42.880
to teach at scale, we need to address all of these challenges. So first and foremost,

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:51.519
relevant and responsive coursework. R, Python, SQL, the common technologies that you find,

00:06:51.519 --> 00:06:57.040
say, in more of a software engineering or computer science type career field, we're going to see

00:06:57.040 --> 00:07:03.839
those same kind of technologies among our employers. So we need to ensure that we are providing students

00:07:03.839 --> 00:07:11.600
with coursework that aligns to employer expectations. The second bullet point for us

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:16.799
is very important. And this was a strategic decision that we made. And I think it's important

00:07:16.799 --> 00:07:26.160
from an academic standpoint that schools make this very purposeful choice. In our case,

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:32.720
it was we want to train business professionals in data and analytics literacy. That is,

00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:41.200
in contrast to we're going to train data scientists in business literacy. So our content

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:48.160
and our coursework is really meant to provide a baseline level of knowledge and understanding

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:56.000
and exposure to analytics, skill sets and technologies, with the assumption that the

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:05.760
vast majority of our graduates are not going to work in analytics specific fields. So for example,

00:08:05.760 --> 00:08:12.320
you might say an accounting student, the accounting field is very much driven today

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:19.359
with an analytics background. But first and foremost, they are accountants and they need

00:08:19.359 --> 00:08:27.679
to be CPAs. And so it's giving a CPA training in analytics to help that individual be a better CPA.

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:36.559
All right. For us, you know, cost of technology is always salient. And that's certainly true for

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:45.840
the higher education industry in general. But for us, being a public urban research university,

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:54.320
we are very cognizant of the heterogeneity in technology skill sets that our students come to

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:59.760
us with. So we will have some students that have very strong technology skills. They've had

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:05.840
exposure with programming in high school, for example. They have strong mathematics backgrounds.

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:11.679
And we will have other students that did not have that opportunity at high school. And so they are

00:09:11.679 --> 00:09:18.719
coming to us with a more modest technology background. That would also be true in our

00:09:18.719 --> 00:09:24.239
graduate programs as well. We might have individuals that are working as software

00:09:24.239 --> 00:09:29.200
developers. And so they are very comfortable with technology and learning new technology.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:35.280
We'll also have individuals that may be coming from a nonprofit administration background and

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:42.880
have had very little exposure to technology. So lowering the cost and the barrier to learning

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:51.119
new technology is a very important consideration for our context. From a school perspective,

00:09:51.919 --> 00:10:00.320
then keeping costs reasonable for technology adoption is certainly also important. The

00:10:02.479 --> 00:10:09.440
criteria are the rapid increase in technology budgets, particularly in the last couple of years

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:17.200
as so many universities shifted to a greater percentage of online teaching or other

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:24.159
digitalization tools has dramatically increased the share of the technology budget from a university

00:10:24.159 --> 00:10:32.880
standpoint. And so areas in which we can keep cost growth reasonable and lowering technology

00:10:32.880 --> 00:10:40.000
complexity is an important consideration. So the last two pieces, I think, tie very well

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:46.719
together in that looking for solutions that address core curriculum and that core curriculum

00:10:46.719 --> 00:10:55.760
might be, say, a course that has, you know, 400 students per year taught across potentially eight

00:10:55.760 --> 00:11:03.359
sections with two or three faculty members. And so having that within course experience taught at

00:11:03.359 --> 00:11:10.479
a larger scale while also being able to provide opportunities for students that want to take

00:11:10.479 --> 00:11:19.520
deeper dives into more technically advanced concepts to have a similar consistent experience.

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:25.280
So just real quick, let me talk about the current solutions because I think this really reflects

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:33.039
where most universities and most business schools are. First and foremost, there's a not just a

00:11:33.039 --> 00:11:41.280
requirement but an assumption for students and employers that Microsoft Excel and competency

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:51.039
and competency with Excel will be a an expectation for a business school curriculum.

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:57.039
And so every business student needs to have a baseline competency in Microsoft Excel.

00:11:57.679 --> 00:12:04.000
For finance and accounting students in particular, these areas where Microsoft Excel is a heavy part

00:12:04.559 --> 00:12:12.559
of employer expectations, these students have to have, you know, a fairly sophisticated

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:18.880
training and exposure to Microsoft Excel. And that's not going away. And I think that's

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:25.039
important when you keep in mind there's always going to be this technology that will be a required

00:12:25.039 --> 00:12:32.559
element of the student experience. But then outside of that, you know, SAS, R, some legacy,

00:12:32.559 --> 00:12:36.559
SPSS, a little bit of Stata. We have, and we'll talk about this a little bit more,

00:12:36.559 --> 00:12:41.599
we have started using RStudio Cloud for some of our graduate courses and we're continuing

00:12:41.599 --> 00:12:46.640
to expand those. And we've had quite a bit of success with that. Python, you know,

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:52.400
certainly in the data science community, Python has, you know, been, you know, a very,

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:58.559
you know, not just emerging but, you know, very prominent technology for some time.

00:12:59.119 --> 00:13:04.320
We're just now kind of seeing interest among employers to have

00:13:07.119 --> 00:13:12.239
employees having a kind of at least a little bit of exposure and understanding of Python.

00:13:12.239 --> 00:13:18.159
And then from a data visualization standpoint, Tableau and Power BI are by far the dominant

00:13:18.159 --> 00:13:25.760
platforms that we find in industry for our employer partners. And, you know, having students

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:32.719
having exposure to those software tools is an important consideration. So I think this is

00:13:33.599 --> 00:13:42.080
important to kind of note that even as we look at leveraging cloud solutions to teach at scale,

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:49.599
it's part of a suite of technology tools. It's not to the point, nor do we really imagine it

00:13:49.599 --> 00:13:56.479
becoming the one solution that allows us to accommodate all of our student needs,

00:13:57.039 --> 00:14:05.599
right? But by the same token, if we can minimize the number of software tools that students are

00:14:05.599 --> 00:14:11.200
exposed to and are expected to learn while still addressing that relevant and responsive coursework,

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:18.559
then that's a very powerful value proposition for the school. And so where would we like to go?

00:14:19.840 --> 00:14:24.799
As we think about, you know, analytics instruction at scale. And so this would be at scale would mean,

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:30.960
you know, we've got 2,000 students that are going to be taking a variety of analytics courses

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:40.400
every year. What we'd really like to avoid is direct installations on student and school

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:46.799
computers. And that really leads to a cloud-centric solution. That addresses a number of

00:14:47.440 --> 00:14:53.359
student issues. One, things like tech support and just the hurdle rate, if you will, of

00:14:54.559 --> 00:15:00.320
spending class time to, you know, install software, troubleshoot software that's directly

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:08.159
installed. It also reflects changes in, particularly among graduate students, where they

00:15:08.159 --> 00:15:15.359
are using, whether that's, you know, a laptop, whether it's a tablet or something that is being

00:15:15.359 --> 00:15:22.080
provided by their employer. And so because of that, they're allowed to use that employer-provided

00:15:22.080 --> 00:15:29.200
laptop for schoolwork, but they can't install software on it. And so this is where for a good

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:37.280
portion of those students, you know, the ability to offer a solution in the cloud really is an

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:45.119
important part of the value proposition. It needs to be laptop and tablet agnostic. So it cannot be

00:15:45.520 --> 00:15:53.359
tied to a particular hardware requirement or a particular operating system requirement. So

00:15:53.359 --> 00:15:59.280
whether that's a Chromebook, whether that's, you know, Mac OSX, or it's a Windows environment,

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:06.640
it needs to be agnostic. It needs to allow for that consistent student experience and allow for

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:12.000
incorporation of multiple languages. And again, it's part of that workflow

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:17.200
situation where students are still going to be expected to learn multiple technologies.

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:27.599
So for example, you might have a course project that is, you know, drawing from Microsoft Excel

00:16:27.599 --> 00:16:36.320
spreadsheets, where a student is going to manipulate, wrangle, and do modeling in RStudio cloud,

00:16:37.280 --> 00:16:44.719
and then a product of that would be exported for visualizations through Microsoft or through

00:16:44.719 --> 00:16:50.960
Tableau, for example. Those kinds of projects and workflows and making it easy for faculty

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:56.960
to develop those kinds of, you know, very immersive, very experiential projects are

00:16:56.960 --> 00:17:01.679
very important. So this is where we'd like to go, but we're not there yet. And we're not there yet

00:17:01.679 --> 00:17:08.479
because of a variety of challenges. And so let me kind of shift a little bit and talk about

00:17:08.479 --> 00:17:14.400
some of these challenges. And I've split these off in financial, technical, and then faculty

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:20.400
considerations. So the first off, it is very important in this context to address the financial

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:26.400
considerations. And here there's kind of two different approaches. One, if the school is

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:32.719
going to be buying the technology, and that could be that the school is absorbing the cost

00:17:32.719 --> 00:17:39.040
of the technology purchases just out of an operating budget, for example, or if they're

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:46.000
going to pass on that cost in the form of a fee to students. But ultimately, the school becomes

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:51.040
the purchaser. So here are some of the challenges if the school is going to be the one buying the

00:17:51.040 --> 00:18:00.319
licensing. You know, the first is flexibility in the licensing agreement. Things that lock down

00:18:00.319 --> 00:18:09.680
or lock up into exclusive relationships, those can be more of a challenge for universities to

00:18:10.560 --> 00:18:17.760
buy into. And there's a variety of reasons for that. But the ability to have some flexibility

00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:24.640
in how they structure the licensing agreement and how it might conform within the context

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:31.920
of other university licensing and licensing rules is fairly important. I think this is

00:18:32.719 --> 00:18:39.839
the flexibility on the part more of vendors than it is on the part of the universities,

00:18:39.839 --> 00:18:45.199
because in many cases, particularly for public universities in the United States in particular,

00:18:45.199 --> 00:18:53.359
there's a number of public regulations and state laws that governs what a university can actually

00:18:53.359 --> 00:19:01.920
do. And so the vendor might desire to, you know, have a licensing agreement that looks a particular

00:19:01.920 --> 00:19:07.359
way, but the university simply can't because they're prohibited under a state law. And so

00:19:07.439 --> 00:19:15.839
having that flexibility is going to be is pretty important. The scalability issue, I think, is also

00:19:18.079 --> 00:19:24.800
you know, a really important question. And that also relates to that per seat licensing question.

00:19:24.800 --> 00:19:33.119
So from the standpoint of if you're going to offer, you know, say in our case, we're going to

00:19:33.119 --> 00:19:41.760
have 2000 students, well, we might have situations where one student might have multiple courses.

00:19:42.560 --> 00:19:50.400
So it's, you know, it's not just per student, but it's per student seat in a variety of courses.

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:58.239
But we may not know what that demand actually is until we're very close to the start of the term.

00:19:58.239 --> 00:20:06.239
And so the ability to scale and adjust very quickly in response to not just enrollment,

00:20:06.239 --> 00:20:13.680
but student demand is an important consideration. It's also important to note that most

00:20:15.359 --> 00:20:22.000
university driven licensing agreements, you know, reflect more of an enterprise type approach

00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:30.400
to software licensing. And so that would be the more you buy, the less you pay per seat.

00:20:31.040 --> 00:20:37.920
And so when the school is the purchaser, having that understanding that we're really kind of

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:44.400
approaching this from an enterprise mindset is, you know, is an important consideration. And that

00:20:44.400 --> 00:20:51.760
can be a challenge because we're talking about potentially very large software purchases.

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:57.839
You know, inevitably require additional time, effort, and energy to navigate through

00:20:57.839 --> 00:21:06.479
the purchasing process. Another, you know, way to look at a financial challenge is if the student

00:21:06.479 --> 00:21:12.400
is going to be the one purchasing the software. And by the student as the purchaser, I mean,

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:21.599
they're going to be the ones who make the buy with the vendor itself. So whether that's a

00:21:21.599 --> 00:21:25.920
credit card or electronic check or something, the university is not involved in any way in

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:34.000
the actual transaction. And I use this term Sesame Street simple. And Sesame Street simple,

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:41.199
it does not necessarily mean, you know, a dumbed down experience. It means an exceptionally clear

00:21:41.199 --> 00:21:49.920
and easy way for students to purchase the license that they need. With a caveat that

00:21:50.640 --> 00:21:55.760
if you're going to do this successfully and roll this out, you are likely to have

00:21:55.760 --> 00:22:02.560
multiple semesters and multiple courses that a student might be involved with.

00:22:02.560 --> 00:22:07.920
So let me give you an example. If you have a student who in a given term is taking two

00:22:07.920 --> 00:22:15.040
different analytics courses, that student may understandably say, I just want to buy,

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:23.040
you know, buy use for one semester and be able to use it across all of my courses,

00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:30.560
as opposed to paying for both courses to use the same software product. Now, that could be,

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:36.239
you know, certainly addressable, but it is an important consideration. And then if the student

00:22:36.239 --> 00:22:42.400
is going to use that software across multiple semesters, then making it very easy to either

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:49.119
renew a license or being able to buy a license for a duration of a program, for example. But

00:22:49.119 --> 00:22:56.239
regardless of what a purchasing approach is used, it has to be simple. And then, you know,

00:22:56.239 --> 00:23:01.439
certainly the cost, you know, if you're already asking students to purchase a very expensive

00:23:01.439 --> 00:23:10.160
textbook or, you know, they are already, you know, experiencing some financial stress because

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:18.239
of additional cost of fees and other requirements to engage with a course, then an expensive

00:23:18.239 --> 00:23:22.560
software purchase on top of that can create an additional barrier and create some additional

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:30.000
friction points. So those are some of the financial challenges. And then it's important

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:35.680
to think about some technology challenges too. You know, student privacy and data network security,

00:23:36.239 --> 00:23:44.640
you know, are not only very salient, but in so many cases are really driving purchase and

00:23:44.640 --> 00:23:53.280
adoption decisions. So any kind of technology that is going to touch student data in some way,

00:23:53.760 --> 00:24:00.079
there is an expectation for a very high degree of security and data integrity.

00:24:00.079 --> 00:24:07.760
Now, I think in a lot of ways, this actually supports cloud-based solutions that are,

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:15.280
you know, that avoid having, you know, data and student records that may be stored on laptops

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:21.920
that can be lost, that can be stolen. So having cloud-based solutions that provide a high degree

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:28.000
of security and integrity, that is an important technical challenge to keep in mind.

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:39.119
Many universities are moving to, you know, what we would think about as a more centralized

00:24:39.119 --> 00:24:43.599
administration of technology resources, not dissimilar from what we would see,

00:24:43.599 --> 00:24:45.839
you know, in other businesses or large organizations.

00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:55.839
The net result being though is a college or school or department may not have organic

00:24:56.560 --> 00:25:04.479
resources to provide technology support, right? So from the standpoint of needing

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:10.319
what we would think of as kind of like help desk type of support resources,

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:15.280
many universities and many schools within universities simply may not have those

00:25:15.280 --> 00:25:21.199
additional resources. So any technology solution, and again, this is, I think,

00:25:21.199 --> 00:25:27.920
favors cloud-based solutions because it eliminates that necessity to install software

00:25:27.920 --> 00:25:33.439
on individual computers, you know, really helps address the question of, you know,

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:41.040
of, you know, limited organic technical support. And then this last piece is also

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:48.880
such an important technical challenge. As schools have gone to, you know,

00:25:48.880 --> 00:25:53.920
the adoption of learning management systems, online course management systems,

00:25:53.920 --> 00:26:00.719
and leveraging extensive technology resources within what we would even consider to be a

00:26:00.719 --> 00:26:11.839
regular classroom-based course, the requirement that these technology tools really must work

00:26:11.839 --> 00:26:18.800
and play well with others is just absolutely paramount. In fact, if it doesn't, that is

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:25.040
a substantial barrier to adoption. And so this could be, you know, things like

00:26:25.920 --> 00:26:32.160
working with Zoom or Panopto or Canvas, you know, some of these other platforms, but also

00:26:33.199 --> 00:26:38.479
the ability to pass student records, you know, student names, student email addresses,

00:26:38.479 --> 00:26:43.760
single sign-on type solutions. All of these things are additional requirements that

00:26:45.040 --> 00:26:52.640
have now become part of the student experience. And so we want to look for ways that minimize

00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:59.040
friction points for students in adopting new technologies. All right, so those are some

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:05.760
financial, those are some technical. And then let me talk about this not as a challenge, although

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:10.640
for some of my fellow faculty members that may be listening, I think you can appreciate that

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:16.800
sometimes faculty, you know, have strong opinions. You know, while I'm a dean, first and foremost,

00:27:16.800 --> 00:27:22.560
I feel that I'm a professor first. And so I can appreciate the importance of faculty

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:29.599
considerations. And these ones that we're going to talk about, I would all put in a similar

00:27:29.599 --> 00:27:36.800
importance category, right? Any kind of technology solutions and a cloud solution, for example,

00:27:36.800 --> 00:27:42.800
must meet all of these requirements. So the first one, and this ties with, you know, what we just

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:48.479
talked about, the importance of integrating with an online classroom management or learning

00:27:48.479 --> 00:27:55.680
management solution, right? And that could be as simple as ensuring that links get populated into,

00:27:55.680 --> 00:28:01.920
but also that assignments, that deliverables, we'll talk about grading in just a minute,

00:28:01.920 --> 00:28:10.880
all of those things can be put in one spot and easily accessed and shared across multiple

00:28:10.880 --> 00:28:19.599
required platforms. Pedagogical flexibility, I think, is another critical piece. And this would

00:28:19.599 --> 00:28:26.479
be, you know, for example, let's take an analytics course where you might have a faculty member who

00:28:26.479 --> 00:28:34.079
prefers live coding as, you know, a, you know, how they prefer to teach their course. And so

00:28:34.079 --> 00:28:38.959
they're going to be interacting with students. They're all going to be coding at one time,

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:45.119
for example. That is how the instructor would like to interact with the technology and deliver

00:28:45.119 --> 00:28:50.319
the course. You might have another faculty member who prefers project-based work that,

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:56.079
you know, classes are kind of meant for discussion, identifying some issues, and then students are

00:28:56.079 --> 00:29:02.719
going to go on their own time, work on projects, develop, you know, deliverables, and then bring

00:29:02.719 --> 00:29:09.680
them back into, you know, a course for discussion. Ultimately, the platform must be able to have

00:29:09.680 --> 00:29:17.520
sufficient pedagogical flexibility to really meet faculty where they're at. And then today,

00:29:19.520 --> 00:29:24.959
when you think about instructional materials, it is very common for textbooks,

00:29:25.439 --> 00:29:33.520
for other kind of packaged curriculum products to have a very kind of integrated approach. So

00:29:34.079 --> 00:29:41.119
quizzes, projects, deliverables, outside readings, everything kind of comes in a package

00:29:41.119 --> 00:29:47.040
that the faculty member can certainly, you know, adopt, not adopt, you know, kind of pick and

00:29:47.040 --> 00:29:52.000
choose. But there is kind of an expectation that these things will all kind of work together. So

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:58.719
when you think about analytics textbooks, for example, you know, many of them today are either

00:29:58.719 --> 00:30:04.079
tied to a software product or, you know, so it could be Microsoft Excel, for example,

00:30:05.199 --> 00:30:14.079
or they are, they have examples across a wide variety of technologies. So you might see, okay,

00:30:14.079 --> 00:30:20.719
here's how we fit a regression line using Microsoft Excel. And then in the appendix,

00:30:20.719 --> 00:30:26.319
they would have something in R and then potentially, you know, Python and, you know,

00:30:26.319 --> 00:30:35.119
Stata and so forth. So having instructional materials that are kind of built for the solution

00:30:35.920 --> 00:30:44.079
is a very important consideration to encourage faculty adoption. Modality flexibility,

00:30:44.560 --> 00:30:50.400
you know, there's certainly as campuses reopen, you know, coming out of the pandemic,

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:56.800
we're certainly seeing more students in class, which is a wonderful thing. But I think we're

00:30:56.800 --> 00:31:03.920
also in an environment now where there is significant expectations from students that

00:31:04.479 --> 00:31:11.439
they might engage with a wide variety of classroom modalities through a degree program. So that could

00:31:11.439 --> 00:31:17.680
be online, asynchronous, where it's recorded lectures, it's, they're really not interacting

00:31:17.680 --> 00:31:23.119
in any kind of live way with an instructor, but they're, they're going to have, you know,

00:31:23.119 --> 00:31:31.040
a heavy online experience, all the way to, you know, a blended classroom where you might have

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:36.800
students in a class and online at the same time, and you're engaging in a fully synchronous

00:31:36.800 --> 00:31:45.199
discussion and classroom activity. So any technology solution needs to be usable in a

00:31:45.199 --> 00:31:52.719
wide variety of course modalities that reflects where we are today as, as an industry.

00:31:53.839 --> 00:31:59.280
You know, student management, and really, this is kind of as simple as who's in my class.

00:32:00.239 --> 00:32:05.040
And students are already registering. And in most cases, learning management systems get

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:10.959
pre-populated with students, they reflect students that add, drop, you know, at various

00:32:10.959 --> 00:32:17.040
points in the semester, you know, faculty members might go and create groups, you know, in these

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:26.400
environments. The ability to ensure that faculty do not have to necessarily duplicate processes

00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:34.400
to ensure that students are added as appropriately to a course, that is an important consideration.

00:32:34.400 --> 00:32:38.800
As would be, for example, the ability to stack courses. So let me give you an example.

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:46.719
As a scale question, you might have 200 students in a semester taking an introduction

00:32:47.680 --> 00:32:54.959
to business analytics course, and they are in four different sections that might be taught

00:32:54.959 --> 00:33:00.079
in a variety of different modalities. Maybe two sections are on campus, one section is

00:33:00.079 --> 00:33:04.719
online asynchronous, and another section is online synchronous, right? So we have,

00:33:04.719 --> 00:33:08.959
we have multiple modalities. We'll keep it, we'll keep it simple. There's one instructor,

00:33:08.959 --> 00:33:13.760
but we have multiple modalities. We have 200 students. And some of those students are going

00:33:13.760 --> 00:33:18.640
to add, they're going to drop, they're going to be in groups. As a faculty member, it's the

00:33:18.640 --> 00:33:29.280
same course. And so I might want to manage my RStudio Cloud course portion that is agnostic

00:33:29.280 --> 00:33:36.400
to which section the student is in. So it's kind of one group of, say, 200, but I need to be able

00:33:36.400 --> 00:33:46.000
to easily manage the lists and manage grading according to that individual section structure.

00:33:46.560 --> 00:33:52.319
And now this would be, you know, very similar to how you might see an experience in Canvas,

00:33:52.319 --> 00:33:59.119
for example, where you're able to, to combine multiple independent sections and manage them in

00:33:59.119 --> 00:34:06.640
one, in one area. Then the grading and student feedback. When we think about the, kind of the

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:16.159
barriers to grading courses at scale. So we've got 200, you know, for example, students are expecting,

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:22.320
you know, a reasonable degree of feedback and interaction with an instructor. And if you have

00:34:22.320 --> 00:34:29.520
multiple deliverables, you know, so let's say you have five projects over the course of a semester,

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:36.159
well, that's a thousand instances that must be graded and returned to students. Now, could be

00:34:36.159 --> 00:34:42.320
the case that artificial intelligence, machine learning solutions, kind of automatic graders,

00:34:42.320 --> 00:34:46.639
those are becoming, you know, a little bit more common. That could be, you know, one possible

00:34:47.199 --> 00:34:53.840
solution, but ultimately the ability to grade easily and to grade quickly and to have those

00:34:53.840 --> 00:35:00.800
grades move into course management systems, you know, that is a very important faculty

00:35:00.800 --> 00:35:07.679
consideration. So ensuring that the faculty member does not have to duplicate a lot of

00:35:08.320 --> 00:35:16.080
effort, because anytime that that's the case, faculty adoption is likely to go down substantially.

00:35:18.479 --> 00:35:25.600
Okay. So let's then, you know, talk about what, what we have been doing to, to drive

00:35:25.600 --> 00:35:29.679
change and drive adoption. So, and I want to, I want to be clear on a couple of things here.

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:38.479
We, as a school, we have a vision for where we would like to go, but we are not yet at the point

00:35:38.479 --> 00:35:45.280
where we are ready to simply turn on a cloud-centric solution and make that our de facto

00:35:45.280 --> 00:35:52.000
standard. Some of that is, you know, reflects that cloud-based analytics software, including

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:56.479
RStudio Cloud, which is a wonderful product, and we've had a lot of success with it,

00:35:56.479 --> 00:36:00.800
is itself still developing. You know, it doesn't have some of those,

00:36:03.280 --> 00:36:10.719
you know, technical capabilities that would really allow us to, to think about using that package to

00:36:10.719 --> 00:36:18.239
teach 2000 students per year, you know, with a very, you know, faculty-friendly and student-friendly

00:36:18.239 --> 00:36:23.520
way. That doesn't mean that the product doesn't continue to advance and get stronger. It absolutely

00:36:23.679 --> 00:36:29.280
is, but it's not quite ready yet, but neither is really anybody else. So, it's, it's also kind of

00:36:29.280 --> 00:36:36.479
important to keep that in mind. The technology itself is still developing, but this first bullet

00:36:36.479 --> 00:36:44.320
point, when we think about driving change and using cloud-based solutions for, for analytics

00:36:44.320 --> 00:36:50.719
instruction, it has to be faculty-centric. Faculty have to be driving it, and there needs to be a

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:58.159
critical mass of faculty that are saying, not just we want to use this product, but we feel that this

00:36:58.159 --> 00:37:06.080
product is better than alternatives, and it's better because we can do more in our course. We

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:13.439
can lower student friction and increase student experience if we use this product, right? And I

00:37:14.159 --> 00:37:21.280
think that, that message, that critical mass from faculty is such a critical piece to this, you know,

00:37:21.280 --> 00:37:29.520
from administration kind of pushing down to faculty, you know, you will, you will now start

00:37:29.520 --> 00:37:36.800
using this to teach your courses is not likely to be a, a productive approach. Instead, it's more of

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:44.000
a, a productive approach. Instead, it's more of a bottom-up, you know, the necessity of a bottom-up,

00:37:45.040 --> 00:37:50.399
which might require some additional faculty education. And, you know, if you have faculty

00:37:50.399 --> 00:37:55.760
who have, you know, been, you know, very used and very comfortable with teaching with a particular

00:37:55.760 --> 00:38:02.239
technology in a particular way, you know, they might, they might be willing to make the shift

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:08.239
and adopt, you know, you know, in this case, a cloud-based solution, but that's going to require

00:38:08.239 --> 00:38:13.280
rethinking their course, potentially rethinking deliverables, and learning the new, you know,

00:38:13.280 --> 00:38:21.040
software product themselves. And so, the importance of having faculty education to help them see how

00:38:21.040 --> 00:38:28.879
they can use this technology to make their course better, that is a critical part. It's also helpful,

00:38:28.879 --> 00:38:33.760
you know, for those faculty members who are, you know, say tenure-track or, you know, they have a

00:38:33.760 --> 00:38:41.840
strong research component, there's certainly value in having a connection to their research technology.

00:38:41.840 --> 00:38:50.320
And I think this is an advantage for R and RStudio because of the adoption in academia of both R and

00:38:50.320 --> 00:38:57.120
RStudio. An advantage of RStudio Cloud is the interface of the cloud product is effectively

00:38:57.120 --> 00:39:03.919
a mirror image of the interface of the desktop product, and so likely to already have some faculty

00:39:04.800 --> 00:39:10.239
with some comfort in R and RStudio, but that's certainly not universal. If I have a faculty

00:39:10.239 --> 00:39:18.479
member, for example, in finance who is very used to Stata, and I'm trying to encourage, you know,

00:39:18.479 --> 00:39:23.679
him or her to think about RStudio Cloud as an alternative, you know, that faculty member may

00:39:23.679 --> 00:39:29.679
very reasonably say, you know, I know how to use this product. I'm very comfortable with it. I,

00:39:29.679 --> 00:39:34.399
you know, I'd rather just not teach the course that you want me to teach if I can't use the

00:39:34.399 --> 00:39:41.360
technology that I'm most comfortable with because that's my research is all tied into that existing,

00:39:44.239 --> 00:39:48.320
you know, into an existing platform. So, you know, important to kind of keep in mind

00:39:48.800 --> 00:39:56.479
that, you know, a research connection, that would be ideal, but certainly not a requirement.

00:39:58.959 --> 00:40:03.199
It's also, you know, in any kind of organizational change initiative, you know, having senior

00:40:03.199 --> 00:40:10.000
leadership support is important, but I would add a little bit of a caveat to this. You know,

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:17.360
certainly having, you know, a CIO or chief data officer or e-learning officer that is supportive

00:40:17.360 --> 00:40:24.639
of the technology, that is very valuable, but I would say it's more the instructional leadership,

00:40:24.639 --> 00:40:31.280
so deans, provosts, chief academic officers, you know, those who have the direct connection to

00:40:31.280 --> 00:40:38.639
faculty that can help address faculty concerns, but also provide, you know, incentives and support

00:40:39.199 --> 00:40:47.360
to encourage faculty to use this technology to improve their courses, right? And then,

00:40:47.360 --> 00:40:53.360
you know, certainly, you know, creative financial solutions. By creative, you know,

00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:58.719
universities are generally under budget and cost pressures from a variety of different ways.

00:40:58.719 --> 00:41:07.679
That is not likely to mitigate in any meaningful way over the next decade. You know, certainly

00:41:07.679 --> 00:41:14.479
varies by, you know, geographic area and around the world, but I think it's probably safe to say

00:41:14.479 --> 00:41:22.239
that on balance, cost pressures are going to be, you know, a meaningful consideration for

00:41:22.959 --> 00:41:27.840
not just for a university that might be looking at adopting this technology, but certainly also

00:41:27.840 --> 00:41:33.919
for students with the increased cost of higher education. So, you know, always kind of keeping

00:41:33.919 --> 00:41:39.280
in mind, you know, sometimes it's a lot easier to solve the technology barriers than it is to solve

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:46.959
the financial barriers, but solving the financial barriers, you know, is certainly a key requirement.

