is probably a little bit steeper than what you would, what would be ideally suited for an

00:49:33.439 --> 00:49:43.199
undergraduate student population that might have substantial variation in technology preparation,

00:49:43.199 --> 00:49:50.320
you know, and literacy. Whereas a graduate program could be perfectly appropriate to use in that

00:49:50.320 --> 00:49:59.840
context. So I think as we've been thinking about it, are there some products that are flexible

00:49:59.840 --> 00:50:08.959
enough such that you can design, you know, course experiences that align with the different student

00:50:08.959 --> 00:50:15.520
populations? And so, and this is where I think we've had some success with the RStudio Cloud

00:50:15.520 --> 00:50:23.120
product, for example, where we're using it in an MBA class that is all about data wrangling,

00:50:24.080 --> 00:50:32.080
what would you consider to be a very analytics heavy course with a high degree of technology

00:50:32.080 --> 00:50:40.399
sophistication. But then we are also using it in an executive MBA course that, you know,

00:50:40.399 --> 00:50:45.520
these are individuals who absolutely are not from strong technology backgrounds, they are senior

00:50:45.520 --> 00:50:51.280
leaders, they are not interested in getting into the nuts and bolts of learning programming,

00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:57.520
but we're still able to use the technology to, you know, create an accessible,

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:06.080
you know, student experience. So I think that's the overarching criteria, Pete, is

00:51:07.199 --> 00:51:16.000
student experience and ensuring that the technology solution doesn't create friction

00:51:16.879 --> 00:51:22.320
in that experience. And then if you can allow for consistency across, then even better.

00:51:23.760 --> 00:51:30.000
That makes a ton of sense. So good news, we have some questions from the audience trickling in.

00:51:30.639 --> 00:51:35.600
So thanks for bearing with me there. The first one, it looks like it says, can you speak more

00:51:35.600 --> 00:51:40.800
to teaching business students analytics? We are developing similar programs and need to

00:51:41.280 --> 00:51:47.600
differentiate from data science. You know, this is such an important criteria, and we struggled

00:51:47.600 --> 00:51:54.800
with this as well. And it gets to that notion that we talked about, what population do we want to

00:51:54.800 --> 00:52:02.000
serve? Do we want to serve data scientists and give them, you know, business skills and business

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:07.520
toolkits? Or do we want to train business professionals with analytics skill sets? And

00:52:07.520 --> 00:52:13.919
I think that difference was how we helped communicate, not just to students, but also

00:52:13.919 --> 00:52:19.520
external stakeholders and senior university leadership, that we need technology solutions

00:52:20.080 --> 00:52:27.679
that help business professionals understand analytics. So they need to be accessible. They

00:52:27.679 --> 00:52:35.280
need to be grounded in a business context. And by business context, this is what businesses are

00:52:35.280 --> 00:52:43.679
using. You know, this is the toolkit that we are finding in business. And business students need to

00:52:43.679 --> 00:52:49.919
have experience with this toolkit. So let me give you kind of a contrast. You might find in a

00:52:49.919 --> 00:52:57.120
statistics department that the department makes heavy use of MATLAB software. You know, for example,

00:52:57.120 --> 00:53:03.439
very robust, excellent statistics and mathematics software. You are not going to go find that

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:11.679
in use in industry. And so I think part of it is ensuring that the technology

00:53:12.560 --> 00:53:19.199
aligns to what employers are expecting and then grounded in that business context. So to the

00:53:19.199 --> 00:53:24.000
question about, you know, teaching, you know, business students analytics, gearing it towards

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:32.479
business problems. So, you know, we might find, you know, a textbook, you know, statistics textbook

00:53:32.479 --> 00:53:39.280
might have a toy problem about, you know, maybe it's a healthcare issue or something like that.

00:53:39.280 --> 00:53:43.760
We might change that and say, okay, we're going to do an analysis of employee compensation.

00:53:44.639 --> 00:53:49.199
Or we're going to do an analysis of customer satisfaction. And we're going to build

00:53:49.199 --> 00:53:56.719
a predictive model of customer churn. You know, the technology and the curriculum is centered around

00:53:56.800 --> 00:54:02.239
a business problem in a very applied way.

00:54:05.760 --> 00:54:10.399
Thank you, Brian. The next question here, looks like we're able to put it on the screen.

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:16.320
There we go. I wonder about the partnership between administration,

00:54:16.320 --> 00:54:21.439
IT and faculty. Our IT has limited ability to implement remote and cloud resources.

00:54:22.239 --> 00:54:26.639
Yeah, yeah, absolutely. I think this is where vendors can play a role.

00:54:28.159 --> 00:54:33.840
You know, the nice thing about cloud-based products is you're already not talking about

00:54:34.639 --> 00:54:41.679
adding existing, you know, hardware or software requirements to the campus IT environment.

00:54:42.320 --> 00:54:46.719
So you've already kind of removed that constraint, which is important.

00:54:47.120 --> 00:54:55.120
I think the other piece of it is vendors providing robust technology support

00:54:55.120 --> 00:55:06.639
that is geared towards faculty and making it very simple for IT staff to deal with this new

00:55:07.840 --> 00:55:12.080
tool that faculty want to use in the classroom. So, you know, for example,

00:55:12.159 --> 00:55:21.439
for example, you know, APIs that vendors have developed to create plug-ins, and we've talked

00:55:21.439 --> 00:55:30.719
about this in the past, Pete, to, you know, plug into Canvas, that the, you know, that plug into

00:55:30.719 --> 00:55:37.840
various ERP systems that are used for student records and grading. I would say those are things

00:55:37.840 --> 00:55:44.159
that vendors need to take the lead on providing because schools just are not going to have the

00:55:44.159 --> 00:55:50.000
resources or the desire to take on that product. If it's, well, listen, you're going to have to

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:54.479
figure out, we'll export the student records, but you're going to have to figure it out. That's,

00:55:54.479 --> 00:56:00.159
you know, that is not going to be, you know, that's going to create additional barriers

00:56:00.639 --> 00:56:08.879
to adoption. And so this notion of partnership, I think, is very critical. I would put faculty

00:56:08.879 --> 00:56:15.919
as need to lead, administration needs to be champions, and IT needs to not be a barrier.

00:56:16.879 --> 00:56:23.280
And I don't mean that in the context that, you know, IT teams are barriers, right? They have

00:56:23.280 --> 00:56:28.320
a tough job to do, you know, they're dealing with a lot of things, and, you know, increasingly

00:56:29.120 --> 00:56:33.199
budgets are very constrained. There are, you know, lots of competition for talent.

00:56:34.080 --> 00:56:42.800
It's making it very easy for them to support this technology. And in some cases that could be,

00:56:42.800 --> 00:56:44.800
they don't need to support it really at all.

00:56:46.959 --> 00:56:53.520
Interesting. You know what, that's a question and topic that comes up often when I'm in various

