here. On the financial constraints of adopting solutions, is it possible to teach how to do

00:58:28.320 --> 00:58:33.120
financial analysis, for example, with R, and what about employment opportunities with this route?

00:58:34.080 --> 00:58:42.080
So, I mean, in terms of the content, you know, teaching financial analysis or ratio analysis or

00:58:42.080 --> 00:58:46.080
some of these, you know, teaching an accounting class, for example, in R and everything that

00:58:46.080 --> 00:58:51.840
goes with it, yes, you could absolutely do that. I would kind of balance that with the expectation

00:58:51.840 --> 00:58:59.840
for Excel skills, you know, just from an industry standpoint. But it is possible to do a lot of

00:59:00.560 --> 00:59:08.800
things like that in R. And I would say opportunities to find complementary uses of

00:59:08.800 --> 00:59:13.840
technologies within some of these more, you know, what it would kind of consider to be more

00:59:13.840 --> 00:59:20.639
quantitatively sophisticated courses, you know, are useful. So you might have, you know, modules

00:59:20.639 --> 00:59:26.800
that have students working in an Excel product. You know, they're doing, you know, different kind

00:59:26.800 --> 00:59:30.639
of analyses, different kind of works. But then, okay, you're going to move it into R, and you're

00:59:30.639 --> 00:59:34.800
going to do, you know, more sophisticated predictive modeling or things like that. And you're

00:59:34.800 --> 00:59:42.560
going to use these tools complementary. You know, that's a pretty powerful combination. And that's

